00:00:45.150 --> 00:00:51.780
So I mean this is really the
most basic part of Fourier

00:00:51.780 --> 00:00:57.480
optics, really, I think so you
need to get lots of practice

00:00:57.480 --> 00:01:06.240
seeing how it all works until
it comes second nature really.

00:01:06.240 --> 00:01:09.950
So this is what
we said last time.

00:01:09.950 --> 00:01:13.760
We went through
this slide last time

00:01:13.760 --> 00:01:18.570
showing the significance
of the point spread

00:01:18.570 --> 00:01:21.210
function of a low pass filter.

00:01:21.210 --> 00:01:27.310
The idea is that if you
put in a point object--

00:01:27.310 --> 00:01:27.810
i.e.

00:01:27.810 --> 00:01:30.830
You put in an opaque
screen with a small hole

00:01:30.830 --> 00:01:33.750
in, illuminate that with
light, this is going

00:01:33.750 --> 00:01:38.460
to then give a spherical wave.

00:01:38.460 --> 00:01:42.060
And then this lens is going to
collimate that spherical wave

00:01:42.060 --> 00:01:44.910
to make a plane wave.

00:01:44.910 --> 00:01:48.680
And in this back focal
plane of that lens,

00:01:48.680 --> 00:01:53.180
you will get a nice
smooth variation here--

00:01:53.180 --> 00:01:58.530
no variation, uniform
intensity, uniform amplitude,

00:01:58.530 --> 00:02:01.130
which is basically
the Fourier transform

00:02:01.130 --> 00:02:02.630
of this delta function.

00:02:02.630 --> 00:02:06.050
Fourier transform of a delta
function is a constant,

00:02:06.050 --> 00:02:07.680
isn't it?

00:02:07.680 --> 00:02:13.010
And then this light then
goes through a pupil mask.

00:02:13.010 --> 00:02:20.480
The plane wave after the mask
then gets to this second lens.

00:02:20.480 --> 00:02:23.390
And the plane wave
is then focused down

00:02:23.390 --> 00:02:27.830
and produces a focused spot
at some image plane, right?

00:02:27.830 --> 00:02:30.050
So that's how it all works.

00:02:30.050 --> 00:02:33.800
And so now what do
you actually see here?

00:02:33.800 --> 00:02:36.050
What's the image of a
single point object?

00:02:36.050 --> 00:02:41.930
What you see is the Fourier
transform of this pupil mask.

00:02:41.930 --> 00:02:45.600
Because again, this is also
producing a Fourier transform.

00:02:45.600 --> 00:02:48.140
Right, so the point
spread function--

00:02:48.140 --> 00:02:51.000
what's called the amplitude
point spread function

00:02:51.000 --> 00:02:56.000
is just the Fourier
transform of this pupil mask.

00:02:56.000 --> 00:02:59.390
And we sometimes talk about
an intensity point spread

00:02:59.390 --> 00:03:02.300
function, which is actually the
model of the square of that,

00:03:02.300 --> 00:03:06.380
the intensity in that
image of a point object.

00:03:06.380 --> 00:03:10.010
OK, so and this is
reminding you where

00:03:10.010 --> 00:03:14.030
you might have come across
this sort of concept before.

00:03:14.030 --> 00:03:18.080
This is like-- we spoke
in the last lecture about

00:03:18.080 --> 00:03:20.270
if in electronics,
you might think

00:03:20.270 --> 00:03:24.350
of an electronic system like
an amplifier or something

00:03:24.350 --> 00:03:26.090
as a sort of black box.

00:03:26.090 --> 00:03:29.810
You put in a signal, and
you get out a signal.

00:03:29.810 --> 00:03:34.730
And you can characterize
that black box

00:03:34.730 --> 00:03:37.850
by what's called the
impulse response, which

00:03:37.850 --> 00:03:43.280
is the response that it would
give to a sharp spike going in.

00:03:43.280 --> 00:03:46.580
All right, so ideally
you'd expect--

00:03:46.580 --> 00:03:49.880
you'd want a sharp spike
to come out as well.

00:03:49.880 --> 00:03:51.500
But in practice,
you don't get that.

00:03:51.500 --> 00:03:55.820
You get some sort
of broader function

00:03:55.820 --> 00:04:00.920
because of the imperfections
of the transfer system.

00:04:00.920 --> 00:04:04.250
OK, so this is our
point spread function.

00:04:04.250 --> 00:04:09.080
And it's denoted-- little
h of x dash, y dash.

00:04:09.080 --> 00:04:11.390
This the x dash y dash plane.

00:04:11.390 --> 00:04:16.459
And I guess this
terminology little h

00:04:16.459 --> 00:04:18.440
seems to be pretty universal.

00:04:18.440 --> 00:04:21.620
Goodman, I think, uses
that in other places.

00:04:21.620 --> 00:04:27.920
All right, so this is
just now describing again

00:04:27.920 --> 00:04:31.460
how you how you
calculate this 4 pi--

00:04:31.460 --> 00:04:34.190
this 4f system.

00:04:34.190 --> 00:04:40.310
We notice everywhere that
the input transparency

00:04:40.310 --> 00:04:43.220
of a delta function
gives one here.

00:04:43.220 --> 00:04:45.890
You multiply by the
pupil mask, and then you

00:04:45.890 --> 00:04:50.520
do another Fourier
transform to find the image.

00:04:50.520 --> 00:04:53.610
All right, so that's--

00:04:53.610 --> 00:04:57.080
I ought to say something bit
more about the scaling of this.

00:05:07.650 --> 00:05:10.080
Yeah, so you've got
of course, this.

00:05:10.080 --> 00:05:14.798
The output point spread function
is a function of x dashed.

00:05:14.798 --> 00:05:17.340
But, of course, when you do a
Fourier transform of something,

00:05:17.340 --> 00:05:22.770
it's going to be a function
of frequency, not of distance,

00:05:22.770 --> 00:05:23.760
isn't it?

00:05:23.760 --> 00:05:28.890
So really this h
here, h of x dashed,

00:05:28.890 --> 00:05:32.400
we get by doing the
Fourier transform of this,

00:05:32.400 --> 00:05:35.910
and then transforming
the coordinates-- scaling

00:05:35.910 --> 00:05:41.050
the coordinates in order to get
it into the coordinates x dash.

00:05:41.050 --> 00:05:43.450
OK, so and then
last time, we also--

00:05:43.450 --> 00:05:45.640
I'll go through this
very quickly, what

00:05:45.640 --> 00:05:52.570
we said last time, if you've
got a low pass filter in 1D,

00:05:52.570 --> 00:06:02.870
like a slip pupil, then the
pupil mask is a rect function.

00:06:02.870 --> 00:06:07.420
And so if we're trying to
calculate the image of a point

00:06:07.420 --> 00:06:11.890
object again, the field when
it gets to this pupil plane

00:06:11.890 --> 00:06:13.460
is just a constant.

00:06:13.460 --> 00:06:16.660
And so after it's gone
through the aperture,

00:06:16.660 --> 00:06:21.390
it will have this sort
of amplitude variation.

00:06:21.390 --> 00:06:26.260
And then so this is
what this is showing.

00:06:26.260 --> 00:06:28.870
On the positive side is what's
on the negative side, which

00:06:28.870 --> 00:06:33.780
is just 1 times
this, which is this.

00:06:33.780 --> 00:06:38.230
And then if you then
Fourier transform that,

00:06:38.230 --> 00:06:41.470
you find that the
point spread function

00:06:41.470 --> 00:06:43.812
is going to be the
Fourier transform of this,

00:06:43.812 --> 00:06:44.770
which is just the sync.

00:06:49.660 --> 00:06:53.540
And then the point
spread function

00:06:53.540 --> 00:06:57.920
is the Fourier
transform of this.

00:06:57.920 --> 00:07:01.013
And then this is doing the
scaling of the coordinates

00:07:01.013 --> 00:07:02.680
and getting it into
the right hand side.

00:07:02.680 --> 00:07:04.055
I'm not going to
go through that.

00:07:04.055 --> 00:07:10.300
We went through it last time,
but hopefully we're going to--

00:07:10.300 --> 00:07:11.220
yeah, here we are.

00:07:11.220 --> 00:07:12.580
And there's the sync.

00:07:12.580 --> 00:07:14.680
Right, so this is that
the amplitude point

00:07:14.680 --> 00:07:18.010
spread function or just normally
called point spread function.

00:07:18.010 --> 00:07:21.670
Note that it goes negative.

00:07:21.670 --> 00:07:23.060
This is 0 here.

00:07:23.060 --> 00:07:25.180
So note that it goes
negative, right.

00:07:25.180 --> 00:07:28.260
So you've got to convolve
that with your objects

00:07:28.260 --> 00:07:32.140
to find the image of some
arbitrary objects, which we'll

00:07:32.140 --> 00:07:34.750
carry on to talk
about in a minute.

00:07:34.750 --> 00:07:39.580
This was just another
example of a phase filter

00:07:39.580 --> 00:07:41.260
and the Fourier
transform of that.

00:07:41.260 --> 00:07:43.635
But I don't think there's
point going through that again.

00:07:43.635 --> 00:07:47.470
We'll just carry on now
where we've got up too,

00:07:47.470 --> 00:07:51.520
which was to do with shift
invariance of the 4f system.

00:07:51.520 --> 00:07:52.570
Now what we find--

00:07:52.570 --> 00:07:56.170
what we've looked at is if we've
got a point object that we get

00:07:56.170 --> 00:07:58.840
from this hole in
the screen, we get

00:07:58.840 --> 00:08:02.080
an image which is this
amplitude point spread function.

00:08:02.080 --> 00:08:06.360
The amplitude here would
be this Fourier transform

00:08:06.360 --> 00:08:09.470
of this pupil mask.

00:08:09.470 --> 00:08:13.370
Then, yeah I'd just mention,
there is this constant.

00:08:13.370 --> 00:08:15.810
This is the point
spread function.

00:08:15.810 --> 00:08:21.080
It's the Fourier transform
of this pupil mass.

00:08:21.080 --> 00:08:23.840
But there's this constant
out at the front.

00:08:23.840 --> 00:08:27.370
And this constant out at the
front is written like this.

00:08:27.370 --> 00:08:31.940
And you can see that it's
made up of two parts.

00:08:31.940 --> 00:08:33.890
First of all, this phase part--

00:08:33.890 --> 00:08:37.700
this just comes about
because of the distance

00:08:37.700 --> 00:08:40.429
the wave is traveled
through the optical system.

00:08:40.429 --> 00:08:43.789
Right, so if it starts
off with zero phase here,

00:08:43.789 --> 00:08:47.660
it's going to come up with
some particular finite phase

00:08:47.660 --> 00:08:50.940
when it travels all this
distance through the system.

00:08:50.940 --> 00:08:55.070
And then the other
bet is this F2

00:08:55.070 --> 00:08:59.420
over F1, which is
a scaling factor,

00:08:59.420 --> 00:09:02.030
the ratio of the focal lengths.

00:09:02.030 --> 00:09:08.365
And basically you need that to
satisfy conservation of energy.

00:09:08.365 --> 00:09:14.030
All right, so you can imagine
that as the point spread

00:09:14.030 --> 00:09:19.100
function gets broader, then
it has to also get lower

00:09:19.100 --> 00:09:22.880
because it has to contain
the right amount of energy

00:09:22.880 --> 00:09:25.620
equal to the energy
going into the system.

00:09:25.620 --> 00:09:28.670
So when you work
out the intensity

00:09:28.670 --> 00:09:30.410
of this image of a
point, this would

00:09:30.410 --> 00:09:34.880
be F2 over F1 squared, which
is the ratio of the heights--

00:09:34.880 --> 00:09:39.200
the maximum intensities
of the center

00:09:39.200 --> 00:09:41.420
of that image of a point.

00:09:41.420 --> 00:09:43.820
Right, now so what we'll be
carrying on to look at now

00:09:43.820 --> 00:09:49.040
is what happens if we
displace our point object.

00:09:49.040 --> 00:09:52.850
We move this delta
function sideways.

00:09:52.850 --> 00:09:54.600
And then let's
look, first of all,

00:09:54.600 --> 00:09:59.150
at just the physical
situation of what's happening.

00:09:59.150 --> 00:10:01.700
This produces a spherical wave.

00:10:01.700 --> 00:10:04.400
And then when it goes
through the lens,

00:10:04.400 --> 00:10:07.030
you can see that it's going
to produce again-- it's

00:10:07.030 --> 00:10:09.770
going to be collimated
into a plane wave.

00:10:09.770 --> 00:10:16.040
But now this plane wave is not
actually moving horizontally

00:10:16.040 --> 00:10:18.200
but is moving at an angle.

00:10:18.200 --> 00:10:21.920
And this comes about because
when you Fourier transform

00:10:21.920 --> 00:10:28.990
this, you will get some
exponential phase factor, which

00:10:28.990 --> 00:10:33.400
actually represents a wave
which is moving at an angle.

00:10:33.400 --> 00:10:37.060
And then when this
inclined plane wave

00:10:37.060 --> 00:10:38.920
goes through the
pupil mask, of course,

00:10:38.920 --> 00:10:40.870
its angle doesn't
change anymore.

00:10:40.870 --> 00:10:44.270
So it's still moving
at the same angle here.

00:10:44.270 --> 00:10:48.640
And then again, it's collimated
and produces an image.

00:10:48.640 --> 00:10:52.900
And the image-- what we find--

00:10:52.900 --> 00:10:55.990
is the same as it was before.

00:10:55.990 --> 00:10:59.540
The amplitude is exactly
the same as it was before.

00:10:59.540 --> 00:11:01.350
But it's shifted.

00:11:01.350 --> 00:11:05.800
So this is what we found before
when we looked at the image.

00:11:05.800 --> 00:11:11.200
You got this-- you remember--
this inverted magnified image.

00:11:11.200 --> 00:11:16.470
The inversion means that it's
the opposite side of the axis.

00:11:16.470 --> 00:11:20.200
The scaling is this F2 over F1,
which comes about from the fact

00:11:20.200 --> 00:11:24.130
that the focal
lengths are not equal.

00:11:24.130 --> 00:11:26.500
But the important
thing to notice

00:11:26.500 --> 00:11:30.790
is that apart from this shift,
this function is the same

00:11:30.790 --> 00:11:31.950
as the function was before.

00:11:35.880 --> 00:11:40.140
So what that means
is that this is

00:11:40.140 --> 00:11:42.450
what's called shift invariance.

00:11:42.450 --> 00:11:44.790
It means that the
image of a point

00:11:44.790 --> 00:11:47.430
is independent of
where the point is.

00:11:47.430 --> 00:11:51.510
Right, so that's a very
important property, which

00:11:51.510 --> 00:11:53.640
simplifies things tremendously.

00:11:56.980 --> 00:11:58.810
Yeah, and here's
a note just to say

00:11:58.810 --> 00:12:03.370
that that is the lateral
magnification of this system

00:12:03.370 --> 00:12:04.460
as we described before.

00:12:09.880 --> 00:12:15.560
OK, so now this is just
showing this diagram again.

00:12:15.560 --> 00:12:18.570
These are not meant
as sort of rays.

00:12:18.570 --> 00:12:22.140
These are just sort of showing
regions where the light is

00:12:22.140 --> 00:12:24.270
as it goes through.

00:12:24.270 --> 00:12:31.890
But we've got this
amplitude here,

00:12:31.890 --> 00:12:34.230
which is Fourier
transformed by a lens

00:12:34.230 --> 00:12:39.726
and then goes through a mask,
Fourier transformed again

00:12:39.726 --> 00:12:40.600
[AUDIO OUT] field.

00:12:43.920 --> 00:12:48.120
So what this slide
is trying to show

00:12:48.120 --> 00:12:51.020
is the significance of
the point spread function.

00:12:51.020 --> 00:12:54.030
At some arbitrary objects--

00:12:54.030 --> 00:12:57.060
we can think of an
arbitrary object g of t,

00:12:57.060 --> 00:12:59.250
an arbitrary transparency.

00:12:59.250 --> 00:13:00.750
You can you can think of--

00:13:03.340 --> 00:13:03.840
sorry.

00:13:03.840 --> 00:13:06.930
You're illuminating
that with some field.

00:13:06.930 --> 00:13:09.990
So what actually you get
after the transparency

00:13:09.990 --> 00:13:11.610
is the products of those two.

00:13:11.610 --> 00:13:15.110
So is the g in that I
really meant to talk about.

00:13:15.110 --> 00:13:17.940
The g in you can think
of as being made up

00:13:17.940 --> 00:13:19.680
of lots of delta functions.

00:13:19.680 --> 00:13:22.830
Any arbitrary function,
you can divide it up

00:13:22.830 --> 00:13:26.280
into lots of delta
functions where

00:13:26.280 --> 00:13:29.160
the strength of each of them
corresponds to the strength

00:13:29.160 --> 00:13:30.938
of that function at that point.

00:13:30.938 --> 00:13:32.730
Right, so this is what
this expression here

00:13:32.730 --> 00:13:34.210
is writing down.

00:13:34.210 --> 00:13:38.970
So the g in is written as--

00:13:38.970 --> 00:13:42.720
you can write it as an
integral over delta functions

00:13:42.720 --> 00:13:44.415
with the strength
given by the function.

00:13:46.940 --> 00:13:49.890
But each of those
delta functions

00:13:49.890 --> 00:13:52.170
is going to propagate
through this system

00:13:52.170 --> 00:13:54.840
and produce a point
spread function exactly

00:13:54.840 --> 00:13:57.430
like we described before.

00:13:57.430 --> 00:14:00.120
And then the image
of the total object

00:14:00.120 --> 00:14:03.300
is going to be the sum
of the images of all

00:14:03.300 --> 00:14:04.990
these delta functions.

00:14:04.990 --> 00:14:09.960
So all of these delta functions
produce point spread functions.

00:14:09.960 --> 00:14:12.930
So you integrate over those
point spread functions

00:14:12.930 --> 00:14:17.070
with the relative strengths
that you need from here

00:14:17.070 --> 00:14:20.580
and you'll get the final image.

00:14:20.580 --> 00:14:24.600
And yeah, you can
see that this is

00:14:24.600 --> 00:14:27.600
a bit like Huygens principle,
that you are breaking up

00:14:27.600 --> 00:14:34.560
this wavefront into lots
of components that are all

00:14:34.560 --> 00:14:36.300
represented as delta functions.

00:14:46.010 --> 00:14:52.630
OK, so therefore what we get out
is going to be this integral.

00:14:52.630 --> 00:14:56.050
Each of these delta
functions is going

00:14:56.050 --> 00:14:59.530
to produce an image given by
this point spread function.

00:14:59.530 --> 00:15:04.150
The point spread function
is shifted a distance

00:15:04.150 --> 00:15:07.830
which depends on the
original distance

00:15:07.830 --> 00:15:10.240
but is scaled according
to this factor we just

00:15:10.240 --> 00:15:12.080
mentioned earlier.

00:15:12.080 --> 00:15:14.560
And the strength
of that component

00:15:14.560 --> 00:15:19.740
is given by this value g in at
this point as we said there.

00:15:19.740 --> 00:15:25.230
So our final expression says
that the output amplitude,

00:15:25.230 --> 00:15:29.160
but amplitude convolved with
the point spread function.

00:15:29.160 --> 00:15:33.360
Right, so this
expression-- you can see--

00:15:33.360 --> 00:15:37.140
is exactly the same as
an ordinary convolution

00:15:37.140 --> 00:15:45.460
expression, except [AUDIO OUT]
But you can see it's

00:15:45.460 --> 00:15:55.730
like [AUDIO OUT]

00:15:55.730 --> 00:16:01.060
OK, yeah so because
of this scaling,

00:16:01.060 --> 00:16:06.060
we can-- and also the
inversion as well,

00:16:06.060 --> 00:16:10.110
we sometimes express
things in terms

00:16:10.110 --> 00:16:13.680
of a reduced optical
output coordinates.

00:16:13.680 --> 00:16:16.230
So we think of the
output coordinate

00:16:16.230 --> 00:16:19.990
as being [? measured ?]
[AUDIO OUT] to get rid

00:16:19.990 --> 00:16:23.560
of the sine and also
scaled it to get rid

00:16:23.560 --> 00:16:25.510
of the scaling factor.

00:16:25.510 --> 00:16:31.450
And if we do it in terms of
these reduced quantities,

00:16:31.450 --> 00:16:34.300
then you can write this as
are just a normal convolution

00:16:34.300 --> 00:16:34.830
expression.

00:16:34.830 --> 00:16:37.240
So all we've done
really is scaled

00:16:37.240 --> 00:16:40.750
the output coordinates
in order to make it

00:16:40.750 --> 00:16:46.350
so that you can use the
normal convolution expression.

00:16:46.350 --> 00:16:50.280
And then we think
back to our case

00:16:50.280 --> 00:16:55.270
