of the number of pixels.

00:51:09.850 --> 00:51:13.750
And therefore if you think of
it as being a binary thing,

00:51:13.750 --> 00:51:15.730
it's the amount of
information that you've

00:51:15.730 --> 00:51:19.300
got in that original object.

00:51:19.300 --> 00:51:22.150
And of course,
that information is

00:51:22.150 --> 00:51:28.700
going to be transferred
through the system.

00:51:28.700 --> 00:51:33.610
So if you look at now the ratio
in the next plane in terms

00:51:33.610 --> 00:51:38.590
of use, this distance
over this distance

00:51:38.590 --> 00:51:41.170
is equal to again,
the number of pixels.

00:51:41.170 --> 00:51:46.720
And as you know, when you
do a fast Fourier transform

00:51:46.720 --> 00:51:48.430
of something which
has got n elements,

00:51:48.430 --> 00:51:50.020
you get something
which is n elements.

00:51:50.020 --> 00:51:52.720
So it all works right.

00:51:52.720 --> 00:51:58.240
So effectively, you can think
of this as being a bit like--

00:51:58.240 --> 00:52:00.430
of course, you can't really--

00:52:00.430 --> 00:52:04.600
if this has actually got
some finite bandwidth, then

00:52:04.600 --> 00:52:07.750
of course you can't
sample on points.

00:52:07.750 --> 00:52:11.560
So it's a bit of an idealization
to thinking this for the terms

00:52:11.560 --> 00:52:12.800
really.

00:52:12.800 --> 00:52:16.270
But nevertheless, it
gives you a good idea.

00:52:16.270 --> 00:52:20.950
So of course, for a repetitive
type function like this,

00:52:20.950 --> 00:52:24.190
also you can think in
terms of a Fourier series

00:52:24.190 --> 00:52:25.870
becomes a Fourier transfer.

00:52:25.870 --> 00:52:28.990
Right, so all we're
doing here is really

00:52:28.990 --> 00:52:35.350
resolving our function
here into a Fourier series.

00:52:35.350 --> 00:52:38.390
And the Fourier series consists
of a lot of sine terms,

00:52:38.390 --> 00:52:38.890
doesn't it?

00:52:38.890 --> 00:52:47.290
Sine of n, and sine
of x, and sine of 2x,

00:52:47.290 --> 00:52:52.390
and so on and so on, and these
correspond in the Fourier

00:52:52.390 --> 00:52:55.210
domain to these
points on this grid.

00:52:55.210 --> 00:52:58.390
Right, so these
each of these points

00:52:58.390 --> 00:53:03.970
represents the particular
Fourier series component

00:53:03.970 --> 00:53:08.050
in the original object if
you think of it like that.

00:53:08.050 --> 00:53:11.080
So the idea of a space
bandwidth product

00:53:11.080 --> 00:53:13.270
is quite a powerful
way of thinking

00:53:13.270 --> 00:53:18.670
about the fundamental
limits of an optical system.

00:53:18.670 --> 00:53:24.920
And people have gone on to
study this sort of approach

00:53:24.920 --> 00:53:28.520
in much more detail,
actually trying

00:53:28.520 --> 00:53:31.790
to get around the limitations
that I just described.

00:53:31.790 --> 00:53:35.450
The fact that, of course,
that we've truncated this

00:53:35.450 --> 00:53:38.980
means that this is no longer
a repetitive function.

00:53:38.980 --> 00:53:41.030
And similarly for here, right?

00:53:41.030 --> 00:53:44.060
So that actually you know
this idea of thinking

00:53:44.060 --> 00:53:47.780
of truncated
repetitive functions

00:53:47.780 --> 00:53:50.330
is a bit of a anomaly, really.

00:53:50.330 --> 00:53:54.530
But people have come up
with mathematical ways

00:53:54.530 --> 00:53:58.700
of dealing with these sorts
of systems which are probably

00:53:58.700 --> 00:54:01.170
way beyond what we are going
to get to in this course.

00:54:04.480 --> 00:54:07.360
OK, did something come up then?

00:54:07.360 --> 00:54:08.080
Oh, yeah.

00:54:08.080 --> 00:54:09.510
Next slide.

00:54:09.510 --> 00:54:13.120
So OK, this is just
pointing out then

00:54:13.120 --> 00:54:18.370
we said that you
put a mask in here

00:54:18.370 --> 00:54:22.850
and that mask produces a
certain transfer function--

00:54:22.850 --> 00:54:27.130
amplitude transfer function, and
the Fourier transform of that

00:54:27.130 --> 00:54:29.000
gives the pupil function.

00:54:29.000 --> 00:54:30.610
And we've shown a
couple of examples

00:54:30.610 --> 00:54:33.700
of what this pupil
function looks like

00:54:33.700 --> 00:54:37.130
and what the image
would look like.

00:54:37.130 --> 00:54:39.670
But this is just pointing
out that actually,

00:54:39.670 --> 00:54:45.710
of course, that means that
we can choose whatever

00:54:45.710 --> 00:54:50.340
we want to put in there in order
to produce the results we want.

00:54:50.340 --> 00:54:52.580
So this is what
George has called here

00:54:52.580 --> 00:54:56.600
pupil engineering, which Ernst
Stelzer doesn't believe in,

00:54:56.600 --> 00:54:59.140
I think, from what
we were saying.

00:54:59.140 --> 00:55:04.790
But anyway, so the idea is
that by changing this mask,

00:55:04.790 --> 00:55:11.150
you can improve the properties
of that point spread function

00:55:11.150 --> 00:55:16.610
in some way, which would suit
the that particular application

00:55:16.610 --> 00:55:17.540
you're looking at.

00:55:17.540 --> 00:55:22.220
Actually, it turns out
that you can't actually

00:55:22.220 --> 00:55:25.670
do a lot better normally
than the very simple example

00:55:25.670 --> 00:55:28.040
of a circular aperture.

00:55:28.040 --> 00:55:35.960
And the circular aperture
is actually very special

00:55:35.960 --> 00:55:40.910
because it does give according
to some measures anyway, a very

00:55:40.910 --> 00:55:43.650
sharp point spread function.

00:55:43.650 --> 00:55:47.870
And you can come up with
other pupil functions

00:55:47.870 --> 00:55:51.560
that make the central lobe
narrower, but normally

00:55:51.560 --> 00:55:56.660
what happens is then the size
of the side lobes get stronger.

00:55:56.660 --> 00:55:58.200
So it's a sort of compromise.

00:55:58.200 --> 00:56:02.180
You can't have a very
small central lobe together

00:56:02.180 --> 00:56:05.540
with very weak side lobes.

00:56:05.540 --> 00:56:08.590
OK, so some examples then.

00:56:08.590 --> 00:56:13.200
So let's imagine first
of all, our object

00:56:13.200 --> 00:56:16.170
is our intensity
at the input plane

00:56:16.170 --> 00:56:21.360
is this rectangle with
the stripy pattern.

00:56:21.360 --> 00:56:24.330
And so we're going
to then look at what

00:56:24.330 --> 00:56:31.050
happens if we image that with
some mask that we put in here.

00:56:31.050 --> 00:56:33.150
And what should we
put in there, then?

00:56:33.150 --> 00:56:38.530
Well, the first one let's
put in something like this.

00:56:38.530 --> 00:56:40.290
So now this is going
to let through--

00:56:40.290 --> 00:56:42.690
this is a low pass
filter, isn't it?

00:56:42.690 --> 00:56:45.870
Right, so it's a very small
low pass filter as well.

00:56:45.870 --> 00:56:50.220
So it only lets through the
very slowly varying parts

00:56:50.220 --> 00:56:52.570
of that object.

00:56:52.570 --> 00:56:57.090
But it stops all the fast
variations of the object.

00:56:57.090 --> 00:56:58.930
Right, so if you
look at the object,

00:56:58.930 --> 00:57:02.130
you'll see that it's got
this stripy pattern, which is

00:57:02.130 --> 00:57:04.800
actually a very fine structure.

00:57:04.800 --> 00:57:07.530
So these are
actually really being

00:57:07.530 --> 00:57:13.250
calculated using Mat lab,
not by me, by George.

00:57:13.250 --> 00:57:17.150
And so this is what you'd see
in the output plane of that.

00:57:17.150 --> 00:57:18.110
So there you are.

00:57:18.110 --> 00:57:21.260
You can see that
this stripy pattern

00:57:21.260 --> 00:57:23.720
has disappeared virtually.

00:57:23.720 --> 00:57:26.960
We've lost some
sharpness at the edge

00:57:26.960 --> 00:57:32.630
though because we've also lost
the high spatial frequencies,

00:57:32.630 --> 00:57:34.880
of course, that
defined the edge.

00:57:34.880 --> 00:57:39.680
And a sharp cut off at the
edge will include quite a lot

00:57:39.680 --> 00:57:42.090
of high spatial frequencies.

00:57:42.090 --> 00:57:47.830
But anyway, so that's a good
example of spatial filtering.

00:57:47.830 --> 00:57:50.880
And then the next
ones we're going

00:57:50.880 --> 00:57:54.070
to look at something which
has got a bit more structure.

00:57:54.070 --> 00:57:59.500
And so this is MIT
written as a binary mask.

00:57:59.500 --> 00:58:02.210
And so this is our
original object.

00:58:02.210 --> 00:58:05.800
And we're going to image
that in an optical system

00:58:05.800 --> 00:58:09.230
and look at what the image
looks like in different cases.

00:58:09.230 --> 00:58:12.650
So the first one is
quite straightforward.

00:58:12.650 --> 00:58:18.820
We've got now a
circular aperture.

00:58:18.820 --> 00:58:21.770
So this is what the image
looks like in this case.

00:58:21.770 --> 00:58:29.780
You see that there's already a
bit of artifacts in that image.

00:58:29.780 --> 00:58:33.850
It's no longer-- you can
still read it as MIT,

00:58:33.850 --> 00:58:36.963
but you see that
inside the letters,

00:58:36.963 --> 00:58:38.630
you'll see there's
some structure there,

00:58:38.630 --> 00:58:40.810
which is not really present.

00:58:40.810 --> 00:58:44.020
So this is some sort of edge
ringing, I guess from the fact

00:58:44.020 --> 00:58:47.680
that this aperture has
got this sharp cut off

00:58:47.680 --> 00:58:52.180
at some particular
spatial frequency.

00:58:52.180 --> 00:58:55.420
So if you made it so that
it tailed off gradually,

00:58:55.420 --> 00:58:58.930
you could probably get
rid of some of that--

00:58:58.930 --> 00:59:01.300
those fringes there.

00:59:01.300 --> 00:59:03.580
But OK, so that's an aperture.

00:59:03.580 --> 00:59:07.550
So we've got rid of some
high spatial frequencies.

00:59:07.550 --> 00:59:13.900
Let's look what happens if we
reduce the spatial frequencies

00:59:13.900 --> 00:59:15.520
even more.

00:59:15.520 --> 00:59:18.290
So this is making
the aperture smaller.

00:59:18.290 --> 00:59:23.070
And now you can see that
the resolution has degraded.

00:59:23.070 --> 00:59:27.010
It looks rather blurry now.

00:59:27.010 --> 00:59:29.020
You can you can't
really see whether it

00:59:29.020 --> 00:59:33.670
says MIT of HIT or maybe HIY.

00:59:33.670 --> 00:59:36.930
It's all getting a
bit vague, isn't it?

00:59:36.930 --> 00:59:41.430
And also you can see that
it gets a bit sort of blurry

00:59:41.430 --> 00:59:43.060
around the edges.

00:59:43.060 --> 00:59:45.118
Yeah, sorry if we make that--

00:59:45.118 --> 00:59:45.910
AUDIENCE: Question?

00:59:45.910 --> 00:59:48.770
One thing to point out here
which is kind of obvious,

00:59:48.770 --> 00:59:51.820
but it's worth pointing is
that if you do this also,

00:59:51.820 --> 00:59:54.220
the average brightness
of the image

00:59:54.220 --> 00:59:57.010
would decrease as you
stop down the aperture.

00:59:57.010 --> 00:59:58.420
But in this case, they cheated.

00:59:58.420 --> 01:00:00.580
They normalized the
intensity to the full level

01:00:00.580 --> 01:00:02.290
so it is visible
in the projector.

01:00:02.290 --> 01:00:05.590
But in a real system, it
would also become less bright.

01:00:05.590 --> 01:00:08.290
PROFESSOR: Right, OK so I
didn't notice that because I

01:00:08.290 --> 01:00:09.570
didn't do the calculations.

01:00:09.570 --> 01:00:10.570
But yeah, OK.

01:00:10.570 --> 01:00:14.235
So of course, if this aperture
gets smaller and smaller,

01:00:14.235 --> 01:00:15.610
the amount of
light going through

01:00:15.610 --> 01:00:17.320
gets smaller or smaller.

01:00:17.320 --> 01:00:21.250
And so in the end,
you'd end up with black.

01:00:21.250 --> 01:00:26.390
Right, so anyway we're now
going to make this even smaller.

01:00:26.390 --> 01:00:29.020
So what would you expect?

01:00:29.020 --> 01:00:31.830
Well, you'd expect
that again the thing

01:00:31.830 --> 01:00:34.070
to become more blurry looking.

01:00:34.070 --> 01:00:36.730
And in fact, it
really does become.

01:00:36.730 --> 01:00:40.240
Just before we carry on,
just take this fully in.

01:00:40.240 --> 01:00:44.860
You notice that there are four
legs here, four straight lines.

01:00:44.860 --> 01:00:46.630
And these two are
closer together

01:00:46.630 --> 01:00:49.960
than these other
spacings, right?

01:00:49.960 --> 01:00:55.740
So as we decrease the
size of the pupil,

01:00:55.740 --> 01:00:57.540
now you see what's happened.

01:00:57.540 --> 01:00:58.600
This is quite amazing.

01:00:58.600 --> 01:01:00.030
I was quite surprised at this.

01:01:00.030 --> 01:01:03.130
The four legs have
become three legs.

01:01:03.130 --> 01:01:07.470
So I guess these two central
legs are now not resolved.

01:01:07.470 --> 01:01:10.770
They're below the
resolution limit.

01:01:10.770 --> 01:01:14.400
And you'd have no idea of
course what that said now.

01:01:14.400 --> 01:01:16.860
It looks something
really blurred.

01:01:16.860 --> 01:01:19.590
So we're not getting enough
information obviously there

01:01:19.590 --> 01:01:27.350
to be able to see
the image properly.

01:01:27.350 --> 01:01:32.520
OK, then let's try doing
some other funny things.

01:01:32.520 --> 01:01:36.870
So this one is a
high pass filter.

01:01:36.870 --> 01:01:39.400
Now, so what we're
doing here is we're

01:01:39.400 --> 01:01:42.190
blocking out this
central part and letting

01:01:42.190 --> 01:01:45.510
through all the other filters,
all the other frequencies.

01:01:45.510 --> 01:01:47.140
Now there's one
other thing that we

01:01:47.140 --> 01:01:51.520
ought to mention here is that
this, of course, is done--

01:01:51.520 --> 01:01:54.790
these calculations are
done using FFTs, right?

01:01:54.790 --> 01:02:00.280
So we're actually working
on a field of a certain size

01:02:00.280 --> 01:02:04.210
when we calculate the FFTs.

01:02:04.210 --> 01:02:06.570
The fact that this--

01:02:06.570 --> 01:02:11.980
as you know FFTs do like a
sort of repeating, don't they?

01:02:11.980 --> 01:02:16.600
Right, so this is not really
quite the same as this being

01:02:16.600 --> 01:02:19.180
going out to infinity
in spatial frequency.

01:02:19.180 --> 01:02:22.750
So I think that the result
in the image you might get

01:02:22.750 --> 01:02:28.000
could depend a little on the
properties of the zero padding

01:02:28.000 --> 01:02:30.640
and things like
that in this case.

01:02:30.640 --> 01:02:33.880
But anyway, this is
the image in this case.

01:02:33.880 --> 01:02:38.930
So you'll notice that we've got
the high spatial frequencies.

01:02:38.930 --> 01:02:42.550
So we actually get some sort
of enhancement of the edges.

01:02:42.550 --> 01:02:46.870
You see the edges come out
really very crisply now.

01:02:46.870 --> 01:02:49.510
So you get this
enhancement of the edges.

01:02:49.510 --> 01:02:52.870
It's like an edge
enhancement filter.

01:02:52.870 --> 01:02:59.360
But on top of that, there's
a rather strange sort

01:02:59.360 --> 01:03:01.670
of glowing patterns,
which I'm not really quite

01:03:01.670 --> 01:03:04.280
sure what they refer to at all.

01:03:04.280 --> 01:03:06.020
But you could-- I
guess-- think of them

01:03:06.020 --> 01:03:08.330
as being some sort of artifact.

01:03:08.330 --> 01:03:11.300
It looks a lot better on
this screen than that one.

01:03:11.300 --> 01:03:12.361
Interesting.

01:03:15.310 --> 01:03:19.000
But if we do another of
these high pass filtering

01:03:19.000 --> 01:03:23.200
but with the central
block even bigger,

01:03:23.200 --> 01:03:27.790
this effect of edge enhancement
shows really nicely now.

01:03:27.790 --> 01:03:30.190
So all we're now
seeing is the edges.

01:03:30.190 --> 01:03:35.080
And the bits inside the letters
are not showing up or outside

01:03:35.080 --> 01:03:37.040
the letters, so neither.

01:03:37.040 --> 01:03:39.370
I can't remember what the
object looked lie now.

01:03:39.370 --> 01:03:41.350
It's interesting.

01:03:41.350 --> 01:03:44.080
The object, whether
it was black writing

01:03:44.080 --> 01:03:45.940
on a white background
or white writing

01:03:45.940 --> 01:03:48.070
on the black background,
probably this

01:03:48.070 --> 01:03:49.952
would look very similar.

01:03:49.952 --> 01:03:51.610
It wouldn't make a
lot of difference--

01:03:51.610 --> 01:03:52.810
I don't think.

01:03:52.810 --> 01:03:58.930
OK, and so all these examples
have been circularly symmetric

01:03:58.930 --> 01:04:00.080
type patterns.

01:04:00.080 --> 01:04:02.080
But you can also, of
course, put in things which

01:04:02.080 --> 01:04:04.180
are not certainly symmetric.

01:04:04.180 --> 01:04:10.310
So this is throwing out these
frequencies here and here.

01:04:10.310 --> 01:04:11.900
So we haven't done
anything here.

01:04:11.900 --> 01:04:14.900
So we're going to have a high
resolution in that direction.

01:04:14.900 --> 01:04:17.800
But in this direction here,
we've reduced the resolution.

01:04:17.800 --> 01:04:23.190
So we'd expect it to be blurred
in the vertical direction.

01:04:23.190 --> 01:04:28.900
And of course, just to prove
that we can do the opposite,

01:04:28.900 --> 01:04:32.090
and this one now is
going to be blurred

01:04:32.090 --> 01:04:33.590
in the horizontal direction.

01:04:33.590 --> 01:04:36.410
So you see here
again, you're almost

01:04:36.410 --> 01:04:41.740
losing the resolution
of those four legs.

01:04:44.460 --> 01:04:52.230
OK, and then probably one of
the most important applications

01:04:52.230 --> 01:04:57.220
of pupil filters is
in phase imaging.

01:04:57.220 --> 01:05:02.760
And so this leads on to
a Zernike face contrast,

01:05:02.760 --> 01:05:08.000
which Zernike got
the Nobel Prize for.

01:05:08.000 --> 01:05:09.170
It's quite interesting.

01:05:09.170 --> 01:05:12.120
It was a long time after he
invented it though, I believe.

01:05:12.120 --> 01:05:14.550
He invented it
sometime in the '30s.

01:05:14.550 --> 01:05:18.755
And it was commercialized--

01:05:18.755 --> 01:05:20.130
actually he seems
to have managed

01:05:20.130 --> 01:05:25.200
to get Zeiss and [? Leicher ?]
and everyone to make it.

01:05:25.200 --> 01:05:30.780
So he must have sold his
patent to lots of people.

01:05:30.780 --> 01:05:33.930
But anyway, eventually
it became very popular.

01:05:33.930 --> 01:05:36.930
But it didn't get it didn't get
the Nobel Prize until the '50s

01:05:36.930 --> 01:05:38.130
some time.

01:05:38.130 --> 01:05:43.640
And very useful
for a long time, I

01:05:43.640 --> 01:05:48.090
think eventually it
got to a certain degree

01:05:48.090 --> 01:05:53.240
anyway, outclassed by
some later techniques,

01:05:53.240 --> 01:05:56.540
but still used a
fair bit in the lab.

01:05:56.540 --> 01:05:59.690
He has one advantage of
being quite cheap as well.

01:05:59.690 --> 01:06:04.220
Anyway, what you're trying to do
with [? phase-phase ?] contrast

01:06:04.220 --> 01:06:06.130
is image of phase objects.

01:06:06.130 --> 01:06:10.550
And this is an example of what
a phase object might look like.

01:06:10.550 --> 01:06:16.910
Imagine, for example, you've
got some glass slide--

01:06:16.910 --> 01:06:20.540
well, one thing which would
approximate quite well to this

01:06:20.540 --> 01:06:23.690
is if you had a
biological cell sitting

01:06:23.690 --> 01:06:25.720
on top of a glass slide.

01:06:25.720 --> 01:06:29.390
Right, so this shows
that something like that.

01:06:29.390 --> 01:06:32.520
But actually what
we're thinking--

01:06:32.520 --> 01:06:34.070
well, if it was a
cell, of course,

01:06:34.070 --> 01:06:35.780
the refractive index
of this would be

01:06:35.780 --> 01:06:37.850
slightly different from this.

01:06:37.850 --> 01:06:44.450
But that's really not
an important difference.

01:06:44.450 --> 01:06:46.600
So this is looking
on the top of it.

01:06:46.600 --> 01:06:49.150
So here we've got
this object, which

01:06:49.150 --> 01:06:51.340
has got a certain thickness.

01:06:51.340 --> 01:06:54.160
And what we'd like
to be able to do

01:06:54.160 --> 01:06:57.850
is to produce an image
which actually shows up

01:06:57.850 --> 01:06:59.830
the shape of this
object, right, which

01:06:59.830 --> 01:07:02.450
might be a cell or something.

01:07:02.450 --> 01:07:06.110
And so this phase object--

01:07:06.110 --> 01:07:10.010
we can think of the light
propagating through this

01:07:10.010 --> 01:07:12.770
and producing a
phase shift then.

01:07:12.770 --> 01:07:16.910
So the phase shift is
given by this expression.

01:07:16.910 --> 01:07:21.680
So n here is the refractive
index of this cell.

01:07:21.680 --> 01:07:25.850
We have to have n minus 1, of
course, because the cell is

01:07:25.850 --> 01:07:27.260
displacing air.

01:07:27.260 --> 01:07:31.130
So the cell wasn't there,
there would be air there.

01:07:31.130 --> 01:07:35.420
So we have to subtract away the
air that would have been there.

01:07:35.420 --> 01:07:39.570
And so the phase is 2
pi times n minus 1 times

01:07:39.570 --> 01:07:43.520
the thickness, which is a
function of x or of x of y

01:07:43.520 --> 01:07:47.340
in this case, divided
by the wavelength.

01:07:47.340 --> 01:07:53.240
And so if we illuminate this
with some certain illumination

01:07:53.240 --> 01:07:57.890
field this, then what we'll
get on the output side

01:07:57.890 --> 01:08:00.430
is just this times this.

01:08:00.430 --> 01:08:04.340
There's no-- each of
the i phi, our object

01:08:04.340 --> 01:08:08.930
just behaves here as
a pure phase object.

01:08:08.930 --> 01:08:11.570
There's no modulus change,
only a phase change.

01:08:15.640 --> 01:08:19.080
Yeah, so useful for
imaging biological objects

01:08:19.080 --> 01:08:21.640
such as cells,
but not only that.

01:08:21.640 --> 01:08:27.560
It's got applications in
material science, and so on.

01:08:27.560 --> 01:08:33.529
And yeah, so if
we looked at the--

01:08:33.529 --> 01:08:38.149
image this illumination
is just unity.

01:08:38.149 --> 01:08:41.689
And we look at the
modulus squared

01:08:41.689 --> 01:08:44.479
of this object function.

01:08:44.479 --> 01:08:47.210
You see, because it's
just only a phase object,

01:08:47.210 --> 01:08:49.310
when you look at
the modulus square,

01:08:49.310 --> 01:08:51.060
you'll see nothing at all.

01:08:51.060 --> 01:08:54.290
So if you look at this in
an ordinary microscope,

01:08:54.290 --> 01:08:55.760
you wouldn't see anything.

01:08:55.760 --> 01:08:59.930
You'd just see completely
uniformly white.

01:08:59.930 --> 01:09:02.720
And so you wouldn't see
the shape of this thing

01:09:02.720 --> 01:09:04.890
that we're trying to see.

01:09:04.890 --> 01:09:07.680
So the question is, how
can we go about that?

01:09:07.680 --> 01:09:10.189
What can we do to solve that?

01:09:10.189 --> 01:09:14.600
So yeah, what we're
now going to look at

01:09:14.600 --> 01:09:18.130
is back to this MIT pattern.

01:09:18.130 --> 01:09:20.250
And we're going
to think of an MIT

01:09:20.250 --> 01:09:24.540
pattern, which is now not
a binary object but a phase

01:09:24.540 --> 01:09:25.500
object.

01:09:25.500 --> 01:09:27.210
So imagine that
this is our object.

01:09:29.760 --> 01:09:32.779
So this represents phase.

01:09:32.779 --> 01:09:40.360
So red represents a phase
change of 0.1 of a radian.

01:09:44.310 --> 01:09:49.590
And this one shows the modulus
of this object, which we're

01:09:49.590 --> 01:09:53.160
assuming is completely uniform.

01:09:53.160 --> 01:09:57.850
And so it's a pure phase object.

01:09:57.850 --> 01:10:00.510
And if we looked at this in
our ordinary optical imaging

01:10:00.510 --> 01:10:05.430
system, all we'd see is the
modular square of this thing.

01:10:05.430 --> 01:10:09.280
So we'd see basically nothing.

01:10:09.280 --> 01:10:14.180
So the question is what can
we do to try and improve that.

01:10:14.180 --> 01:10:17.080
Well, Zernike came
up with the answer.

01:10:17.080 --> 01:10:20.270
And actually, this is not
quite the way he does it.

01:10:20.270 --> 01:10:22.270
We're not going to really
do the way he does it.

01:10:22.270 --> 01:10:26.260
But the principle
is here anyway.

01:10:26.260 --> 01:10:31.360
What you do is you introduce
a pupil mask, which has also

01:10:31.360 --> 01:10:34.000
got a phase objects in it.

01:10:34.000 --> 01:10:38.320
It's got basically
a small region

01:10:38.320 --> 01:10:43.090
at the center, i.e. where the
low spatial frequencies are,

01:10:43.090 --> 01:10:46.450
which we change
the relative phase

01:10:46.450 --> 01:10:50.290
of those spectral components
relative to the other spatial

01:10:50.290 --> 01:10:54.760
frequencies by pi over 2.

01:10:54.760 --> 01:10:58.330
And so we put that
in our in our system.

01:11:05.990 --> 01:11:08.120
And what we find,
as it says there,

01:11:08.120 --> 01:11:13.070
is we can actually get
contrast of the phase.

01:11:13.070 --> 01:11:16.080
We actually see the phase now.

01:11:16.080 --> 01:11:18.030
And this will explain
why that works.

01:11:18.030 --> 01:11:19.230
So this is what we're doing.

01:11:19.230 --> 01:11:22.440
We're putting in our
phase MIT thing here.

01:11:22.440 --> 01:11:26.090
And we're putting in this
pi over 2 phase mask here.

01:11:31.900 --> 01:11:34.740
So that's what it looks like.

01:11:34.740 --> 01:11:37.530
It's some bit of
dielectric, which

01:11:37.530 --> 01:11:39.600
has got this
central region which

01:11:39.600 --> 01:11:43.200
changes the phase by pi over 2.

01:11:43.200 --> 01:11:46.680
Ideally, what we want
to do, as it says here,

01:11:46.680 --> 01:11:48.930
is for this to be very small.

01:11:48.930 --> 01:11:50.610
What we're trying
to do is to use

01:11:50.610 --> 01:11:54.600
it to change the phase
of just the DC component,

01:11:54.600 --> 01:11:59.400
the unscattered light component
relative to all the rest.

01:11:59.400 --> 01:12:02.220
But of course, you can
never do that because it's

01:12:02.220 --> 01:12:06.840
got to have some
definite real size.

01:12:06.840 --> 01:12:11.070
So whatever size
it is, there might

01:12:11.070 --> 01:12:15.270
be some low spatial frequencies
of the object, which

01:12:15.270 --> 01:12:17.105
are going to be--

01:12:17.105 --> 01:12:18.480
the phase is going
to be changing

01:12:18.480 --> 01:12:22.320
in the same way as the DC term.

01:12:22.320 --> 01:12:25.870
So let's look at the
mass of how that works.

01:12:25.870 --> 01:12:30.240
So what we do is we assume
our phase object is what

01:12:30.240 --> 01:12:33.080
we call a weak phase object.

01:12:33.080 --> 01:12:37.250
It's got the form
e to the i phi.

01:12:37.250 --> 01:12:42.720
But we think of that as being
approximately one plus i phi.

01:12:42.720 --> 01:12:44.990
And we neglect all
the other higher order

01:12:44.990 --> 01:12:53.660
terms in the Haus's series
expansion for the exponential.

01:12:53.660 --> 01:12:58.670
And you can see then that in an
ordinary system, what we'd see

01:12:58.670 --> 01:13:02.810
is you can think of it--

01:13:02.810 --> 01:13:05.630
keeping all the terms,
the modular square of this

01:13:05.630 --> 01:13:07.660
is obviously one.

01:13:07.660 --> 01:13:10.130
And this also,
the modular square

01:13:10.130 --> 01:13:14.210
of this to the first
order of small quantities

01:13:14.210 --> 01:13:15.610
is also going to be one.

01:13:15.610 --> 01:13:19.550
Of course, if you square this,
you'll get phi squared terms.

01:13:19.550 --> 01:13:21.260
But actually, there
are also really

01:13:21.260 --> 01:13:25.980
some extra phi squared terms
in this series, which actually,

01:13:25.980 --> 01:13:28.740
if you do it properly,
all cancel out.

01:13:28.740 --> 01:13:29.930
So you still must get one.

01:13:35.360 --> 01:13:39.440
OK, so what we're now going
to say, this is our object.

01:13:39.440 --> 01:13:44.210
But now, this object is going
to go through this mask here,

01:13:44.210 --> 01:13:48.200
which is going to change the
relative phase of this relative

01:13:48.200 --> 01:13:49.770
to this.

01:13:49.770 --> 01:13:54.920
And so if we change
the one to i,

01:13:54.920 --> 01:13:58.580
we're not going to
get i plus i phi.

01:13:58.580 --> 01:14:01.520
And therefore now,
the output that we get

01:14:01.520 --> 01:14:02.780
is going to be given by--

01:14:05.720 --> 01:14:08.520
this should be into
i, intensity actually.

01:14:08.520 --> 01:14:12.740
Yeah, the intensity that you
see is the modular square

01:14:12.740 --> 01:14:17.840
of this, which is 1 plus phi
squared, which to small--

01:14:17.840 --> 01:14:21.100
Because phi is small,
we can expand that

01:14:21.100 --> 01:14:24.560
to first two terms
of the series.

01:14:24.560 --> 01:14:26.900
And we get one plus two phi.

01:14:26.900 --> 01:14:31.340
Right, so now we're getting
an image where the phase is

01:14:31.340 --> 01:14:34.730
visible to the order of this--

01:14:34.730 --> 01:14:39.200
order of the weak
phase object phi.

01:14:39.200 --> 01:14:42.230
In this case here, we
weren't seeing anything

01:14:42.230 --> 01:14:43.660
to the order of phi.

01:14:43.660 --> 01:14:46.340
The lowest things
that were there

01:14:46.340 --> 01:14:49.280
would be of the order
of phi squared, which

01:14:49.280 --> 01:14:54.050
is going to be negligible if
phi is going to be small enough.

01:14:54.050 --> 01:14:55.050
Right, so there we are.

01:14:55.050 --> 01:14:58.010
So by putting this
in, we've managed

01:14:58.010 --> 01:15:02.030
to make this phase
object visible.

01:15:02.030 --> 01:15:04.910
So this is the
demonstration of that.

01:15:04.910 --> 01:15:09.830
So this is our looking
out at our phase MIT.

01:15:09.830 --> 01:15:14.010
And this is the size
of our phase mask.

01:15:14.010 --> 01:15:16.490
So it's quite big here actually.

01:15:16.490 --> 01:15:25.970
And so I guess, it's changing
the phase of the central DC

01:15:25.970 --> 01:15:26.810
term.

01:15:26.810 --> 01:15:30.770
But it's also changing the phase
of some low spatial frequency

01:15:30.770 --> 01:15:35.210
terms of the MIT,
which I guess accounts

01:15:35.210 --> 01:15:39.770
for some sort of
imperfections in this image.

01:15:39.770 --> 01:15:41.960
And I think a lot
of the ripples--

01:15:41.960 --> 01:15:44.870
again, are coming from
the fact that this

01:15:44.870 --> 01:15:48.290
has got a sharp edge to it.

01:15:48.290 --> 01:15:50.120
Probably if you
smoothed this, you

01:15:50.120 --> 01:15:53.870
could make it so that you
didn't get such a strong ringing

01:15:53.870 --> 01:15:54.740
in this thing here.

01:15:58.480 --> 01:16:01.510
But this is the next example.

01:16:01.510 --> 01:16:04.150
We've now made
this a lot smaller.

01:16:04.150 --> 01:16:08.800
So it's now changing the
phase of the DC term.

01:16:08.800 --> 01:16:10.870
But it seems that the
object itself probably

01:16:10.870 --> 01:16:14.830
has got very, very weak
components in that region.

01:16:14.830 --> 01:16:19.790
And you end up then with
this really wonderful image.

01:16:19.790 --> 01:16:28.450
So I guess that really shows
the power of the Zernike phase

01:16:28.450 --> 01:16:29.370
contrast method.

