01:32:26.650 --> 01:32:29.630
Well, there is the physical
explanation, which is probably

01:32:29.630 --> 01:32:33.410
the most interesting.

01:32:33.410 --> 01:32:35.450
And that has to do
with the following.

01:32:35.450 --> 01:32:39.320
So this really goes to
the heart of diffraction,

01:32:39.320 --> 01:32:41.690
why really diffraction
happens and why

01:32:41.690 --> 01:32:43.950
we see all of this phenomenon.

01:32:43.950 --> 01:32:47.550
So imagine that you
have a plane wave going

01:32:47.550 --> 01:32:51.390
into a sinusoid
amplitude gradient.

01:32:51.390 --> 01:32:53.860
And of course, in this case
you only get three diffraction

01:32:53.860 --> 01:32:56.900
orders, as we discussed,
the plus 1, the minus 1,

01:32:56.900 --> 01:32:58.860
and the [INAUDIBLE]

01:32:58.860 --> 01:33:01.680
And these diffraction
orders, each one of them

01:33:01.680 --> 01:33:03.300
is really a plane wave.

01:33:03.300 --> 01:33:04.520
So you have now--

01:33:04.520 --> 01:33:07.790
you started with one coming
in, but after the gradient,

01:33:07.790 --> 01:33:11.930
you have three plane
waves propagating out.

01:33:11.930 --> 01:33:15.270
And imagine that you pick any
point of the gradient really,

01:33:15.270 --> 01:33:16.230
it doesn't matter.

01:33:16.230 --> 01:33:18.090
But let's pick this one.

01:33:18.090 --> 01:33:22.820
And we'll draw a
sphere over radius z.

01:33:22.820 --> 01:33:26.190
we'll draw a sphere
centered at this point.

01:33:26.190 --> 01:33:28.170
Now if you compare
the three plane waves

01:33:28.170 --> 01:33:33.450
and you take rays
really, centered

01:33:33.450 --> 01:33:35.760
at the center of this
sphere, and if you

01:33:35.760 --> 01:33:41.130
compare what happens to
these plane waves by the time

01:33:41.130 --> 01:33:43.440
that each of the
cell of this sphere,

01:33:43.440 --> 01:33:47.340
then you realize that they
all have the same phase delay

01:33:47.340 --> 01:33:50.910
because they only propagated the
same distance from the center

01:33:50.910 --> 01:33:52.130
to the edge of this sphere.

01:33:52.130 --> 01:33:53.980
They all propagated
by the same amount.

01:33:53.980 --> 01:33:55.920
So they have the
same phase delay.

01:33:55.920 --> 01:33:59.370
However, when we
observe the field

01:33:59.370 --> 01:34:01.740
in all of this cross-section
that I showed before

01:34:01.740 --> 01:34:04.290
in my movie and in
the calculation,

01:34:04.290 --> 01:34:07.140
I did not really observe
the field on a sphere.

01:34:07.140 --> 01:34:09.400
I observed it on a plane.

01:34:09.400 --> 01:34:14.430
So if a center this plane at
a distance z from the axis,

01:34:14.430 --> 01:34:18.150
then the central order
that propagates a axis,

01:34:18.150 --> 01:34:20.430
it sustains itself
in phase delay.

01:34:20.430 --> 01:34:24.450
But you can see that the
plus one and minus one order,

01:34:24.450 --> 01:34:27.660
they propagate the longer
distance from this sphere

01:34:27.660 --> 01:34:28.920
to that gradient.

01:34:28.920 --> 01:34:30.760
And you can calculate
this distance.

01:34:30.760 --> 01:34:34.090
It is the difference
between the z itself

01:34:34.090 --> 01:34:38.060
and an expansion that is that
you get from its Pythagoras's

01:34:38.060 --> 01:34:39.150
theorem.

01:34:39.150 --> 01:34:43.890
So this expression is basically
the hypotenuse of this triangle

01:34:43.890 --> 01:34:47.780
all the way out to the plane.

01:34:47.780 --> 01:34:50.090
And if you do after that
the paraxial approximation,

01:34:50.090 --> 01:34:51.882
then you find that is
given by a quadratic.

01:34:51.882 --> 01:34:54.500
That is this is our
familiar quadratic term that

01:34:54.500 --> 01:34:58.510
appears in the Fresnel kernel
and in all of these expressions

01:34:58.510 --> 01:35:01.040
of Fresnel diffraction.

01:35:01.040 --> 01:35:06.930
So however, now what
am I really observing?

01:35:06.930 --> 01:35:10.520
Well, in this plane, I observe
the interference pattern.

01:35:10.520 --> 01:35:12.740
You can think of it as
a Fresnel diffraction

01:35:12.740 --> 01:35:15.140
pattern from the
gradient or you can also

01:35:15.140 --> 01:35:17.930
think of it as an interference
pattern between these three

01:35:17.930 --> 01:35:19.550
plane waves.

01:35:19.550 --> 01:35:22.940
It's like an
interferometer, right?

01:35:22.940 --> 01:35:25.460
I mean, physically as I
think Professor separately

01:35:25.460 --> 01:35:28.520
mentioned and I also mentioned
at some point or another,

01:35:28.520 --> 01:35:31.198
diffraction is really no
different than interference.

01:35:31.198 --> 01:35:32.990
It is just that in the
case of diffraction,

01:35:32.990 --> 01:35:35.990
you have many, many, many
waves interfering produced

01:35:35.990 --> 01:35:39.210
by the Huygen's
wavelengths originating

01:35:39.210 --> 01:35:41.120
at your original object.

01:35:41.120 --> 01:35:42.830
But in this case,
instead of thinking

01:35:42.830 --> 01:35:44.630
of all these
Huygens wavelengths,

01:35:44.630 --> 01:35:47.030
I'm better off just
thinking about it

01:35:47.030 --> 01:35:49.760
as plane waves interfering
because the physics

01:35:49.760 --> 01:35:53.330
of the gradient tell me that
the diffracting field is really

01:35:53.330 --> 01:35:56.210
composed of three plane waves.

01:35:56.210 --> 01:36:01.460
So now there's a phase delay
between this guy and this guy.

01:36:01.460 --> 01:36:04.900
Actually, this guy and this
guy, the plus 1 and minus 1

01:36:04.900 --> 01:36:06.800
are always in phase.

01:36:06.800 --> 01:36:10.790
But they can have a
difference in phase delay

01:36:10.790 --> 01:36:14.690
between the themselves
and the 0-th order.

01:36:14.690 --> 01:36:18.870
And of course, if that phase
delay happens to be 2 pi,

01:36:18.870 --> 01:36:20.640
then there's no phase delay.

01:36:20.640 --> 01:36:25.470
And when did these things
start having no phase delay?

01:36:25.470 --> 01:36:27.720
Well, at the gradient, right?

01:36:27.720 --> 01:36:30.840
So if I let this thing
propagate enough, whatever

01:36:30.840 --> 01:36:33.810
parameter I can vary here is z.

01:36:33.810 --> 01:36:37.530
If I let z grow so that
this phase delay becomes

01:36:37.530 --> 01:36:40.860
equal to 2 pi, then I
reproduced my original gradient

01:36:40.860 --> 01:36:45.105
because of course, there
was no phase delay here.

01:36:47.870 --> 01:36:49.960
So when the phase
delay becomes 2 pi,

01:36:49.960 --> 01:36:53.420
then again I will
see the same pattern.

01:36:53.420 --> 01:37:04.480
It is not as obvious why
you get the subharmonic, why

01:37:04.480 --> 01:37:07.360
you get the second harmonic
that I discussed before.

