actually get rid of the DC

01:37:21.520 --> 01:37:23.440
component, you can get
the second harmonic

01:37:23.440 --> 01:37:26.330
to pop out all of a sudden.

01:37:26.330 --> 01:37:29.200
A very similar thing happens
if you get the pi phase shift.

01:37:29.200 --> 01:37:32.268
This pi phase shift can produce
a very distinct sub harmonic.

01:37:32.268 --> 01:37:33.226
So this is that reason.

01:37:38.860 --> 01:37:42.393
Now the rest, I will
actually not go through.

01:37:42.393 --> 01:37:43.810
But there's a
mathematical-- well,

01:37:43.810 --> 01:37:45.435
I can go through very
quickly, I guess.

01:37:45.435 --> 01:37:47.730
There's a mathematical
way to derive it.

01:37:47.730 --> 01:37:49.510
And it is also
described in Goodman.

01:37:49.510 --> 01:37:51.780
And I also did it in the slides.

01:37:51.780 --> 01:37:55.620
So if you start with
a grate with a field

01:37:55.620 --> 01:37:57.880
after the gradient--

01:37:57.880 --> 01:38:00.130
of course, you can express
it as a diffraction orders.

01:38:00.130 --> 01:38:03.040
We did this before.

01:38:03.040 --> 01:38:06.880
You can put it in a form the
field after the gradient.

01:38:06.880 --> 01:38:10.340
We've done this before ask in
the context of the 4f system.

01:38:10.340 --> 01:38:12.130
But mathematically,
it is really the same.

01:38:12.130 --> 01:38:14.800
Each one of these
exponentials in the field

01:38:14.800 --> 01:38:17.000
will produce a delta function.

01:38:17.000 --> 01:38:18.760
Now, the question
is what happens

01:38:18.760 --> 01:38:23.060
after the field propagates
by a certain distance.

01:38:23.060 --> 01:38:28.870
So in order to do that, let me
show the Fresnel diffraction

01:38:28.870 --> 01:38:29.680
again.

01:38:29.680 --> 01:38:31.290
These we're familiar with.

01:38:31.290 --> 01:38:34.180
We said many times that
Fresnel diffraction

01:38:34.180 --> 01:38:36.400
is expressed as a
convolution that

01:38:36.400 --> 01:38:38.170
has to do with the
Huygen's wavelengths

01:38:38.170 --> 01:38:40.780
propagating and producing
spherical waves that

01:38:40.780 --> 01:38:42.100
again interfere.

01:38:42.100 --> 01:38:45.520
So the interference is expressed
as a convolution integral.

01:38:45.520 --> 01:38:49.600
But because of the properties
of the Fourier transform,

01:38:49.600 --> 01:38:52.750
if I take a Fourier transform
of the output field,

01:38:52.750 --> 01:38:56.270
then it will be expressed
as a product of the Fourier

01:38:56.270 --> 01:39:00.790
transform of the input field
times the Fourier transform

01:39:00.790 --> 01:39:04.660
of this Fresnel kernel.

01:39:04.660 --> 01:39:08.020
And I really am not
going to prove this.

01:39:08.020 --> 01:39:12.490
But you can look up in Goodman's
book in the table of Fourier

01:39:12.490 --> 01:39:13.390
integrals.

01:39:13.390 --> 01:39:15.820
You can look up the
Fourier transform

01:39:15.820 --> 01:39:18.070
of an expression like this one.

01:39:18.070 --> 01:39:20.770
And you'll find that
it looks very similar.

01:39:20.770 --> 01:39:24.158
This is a quadratic phase delay

01:39:24.158 --> 01:39:25.200
It's a Fourier transform.

01:39:25.200 --> 01:39:28.240
It also looks like a
quadratic phase delay.

01:39:28.240 --> 01:39:30.350
But it has two key differences.

01:39:30.350 --> 01:39:32.020
One is that it has a minus sign.

01:39:32.020 --> 01:39:35.070
So it is actually quadratic
phase advance if you wish.

01:39:35.070 --> 01:39:37.450
And the second is, of course,
the [? scalene ?] theorem

01:39:37.450 --> 01:39:41.690
that will take up this factor
of lambda z from the denominator

01:39:41.690 --> 01:39:43.750
and will pop it up
in the numerator.

01:39:43.750 --> 01:39:47.440
And of course, the happy
outcome of this scale operation

01:39:47.440 --> 01:39:50.260
is that also the
units are preserved.

01:39:50.260 --> 01:39:52.414
This quantity has
to be dimensionless.

01:39:52.414 --> 01:39:53.122
So indeed, it is.

01:39:53.122 --> 01:39:56.560
I have distance square
in the numerator

01:39:56.560 --> 01:39:58.240
as well as the denominator.

01:39:58.240 --> 01:40:00.320
In this case it uses
spatial frequency which

01:40:00.320 --> 01:40:02.980
is inverse distance square.

01:40:02.980 --> 01:40:05.500
By multiplying by
this distance squared,

01:40:05.500 --> 01:40:07.490
I get again a one
dimensional quantity.

01:40:07.490 --> 01:40:10.030
So the [? scalene ?]
theorem works quite nicely.

01:40:10.030 --> 01:40:15.570
And you can also think then of--

01:40:15.570 --> 01:40:17.490
we talked about
transfer functions

01:40:17.490 --> 01:40:20.003
in the context
over the 4f system.

01:40:20.003 --> 01:40:22.170
But really you can also
think of a transfer function

01:40:22.170 --> 01:40:24.360
in the case of
Fresnel propagation

01:40:24.360 --> 01:40:26.070
because it is shift invariant.

01:40:26.070 --> 01:40:29.430
Clearly if you have free
space, that is it truly

01:40:29.430 --> 01:40:30.930
a shift invariant system.

01:40:30.930 --> 01:40:33.060
No matter where you
start in free space,

01:40:33.060 --> 01:40:37.110
you would expect the field
to shift by the same amount.

01:40:37.110 --> 01:40:40.800
It would be really odd if
anything else happened.

01:40:40.800 --> 01:40:43.470
Unless you believe in space
and [INAUDIBLE] I guess.

01:40:43.470 --> 01:40:48.390
Only close to the Big Bang,
this property was not observed.

01:40:48.390 --> 01:40:51.720
But since billions of years
have lapsed since the Big Bang,

01:40:51.720 --> 01:40:53.082
space is isotropic.

01:40:53.082 --> 01:40:54.540
So we don't have
to worry about it.

01:40:54.540 --> 01:40:58.110
So of course, the Fourier
integral approaches.

01:40:58.110 --> 01:41:00.540
And of course, then this
quantity that we derive

01:41:00.540 --> 01:41:03.060
is simply the transfer
function of free space.

01:41:03.060 --> 01:41:07.190
It is another
quadratic phase delay.

01:41:07.190 --> 01:41:11.120
OK, so we can actually
apply this formulation now

01:41:11.120 --> 01:41:13.230
to the mathematics
of the Talbot effect.

01:41:27.990 --> 01:41:31.780
All I have to do is multiply
the Fourier transform

01:41:31.780 --> 01:41:34.840
of the gradient itself.

01:41:34.840 --> 01:41:37.650
All I have to do is multiply
it with a Fourier transform

01:41:37.650 --> 01:41:40.250
of the Fresnel
propagation kernel that is

01:41:40.250 --> 01:41:42.355
another quadratic phase delay.

01:41:42.355 --> 01:41:44.230
And this multiple
multiplication is very easy

01:41:44.230 --> 01:41:46.300
to do because I'm
multiplying the function

01:41:46.300 --> 01:41:49.130
that I know with a bunch
of delta functions.

01:41:49.130 --> 01:41:54.400
So all that will remain
really is the value

01:41:54.400 --> 01:42:00.760
of this quadratic phase
delay computed at the spots

01:42:00.760 --> 01:42:04.340
where the delta
functions occurred.

01:42:04.340 --> 01:42:06.200
And this is what I'm
doing the next slide.

01:42:08.970 --> 01:42:12.720
This looks a little
bit nasty but really

01:42:12.720 --> 01:42:15.890
that's all you need to know.

01:42:15.890 --> 01:42:19.190
It looks like an expression
very similar to the gradient.

01:42:19.190 --> 01:42:20.820
This is the DC component.

01:42:20.820 --> 01:42:22.610
This is the plus one
diffracted order.

01:42:22.610 --> 01:42:24.980
This is a minus one
diffracted order.

01:42:24.980 --> 01:42:29.000
But it picked up this additional
quadratic phase delay,

01:42:29.000 --> 01:42:31.210
which is really it came
out of the math now.

01:42:31.210 --> 01:42:33.350
I used Fourier transforms
and convolutions

01:42:33.350 --> 01:42:34.500
and everything else.

01:42:34.500 --> 01:42:43.070
But if you go back to my
picture here with the sphere

01:42:43.070 --> 01:42:45.530
and the phase delays,
you can really

01:42:45.530 --> 01:42:49.520
see that this is really
the same expression.

01:42:49.520 --> 01:42:51.400
It came out of the
math in one case.

01:42:51.400 --> 01:42:54.140
It really came out
of a physical picture

01:42:54.140 --> 01:42:56.390
of phase delay of [? planes ?]
as they propagate.

01:42:56.390 --> 01:42:57.390
But it's all consistent.

01:42:57.390 --> 01:43:04.010
It is nearly all
the same answer.

01:43:04.010 --> 01:43:06.950
And after a little
bit more pain,

01:43:06.950 --> 01:43:16.080
which involves really taking
one Fourier transform,

01:43:16.080 --> 01:43:22.970
and then combining these
things to form a sinusoid,

01:43:22.970 --> 01:43:26.210
you'll get this
expression for the field.

01:43:26.210 --> 01:43:31.160
And now you can see what I
was saying before, if you--

01:43:31.160 --> 01:43:32.830
this looks like a
nasty phase delay

01:43:32.830 --> 01:43:34.940
that got appended to
the diffracted field.

01:43:34.940 --> 01:43:36.740
This is really
diffracted field now.

01:43:36.740 --> 01:43:38.540
So this is the Fresnel
diffraction pattern

01:43:38.540 --> 01:43:39.770
from a gradient.

01:43:39.770 --> 01:43:45.780
But if this quantity and
exponent happens to be 2 pi,

01:43:45.780 --> 01:43:47.180
then it is not there anymore.

01:43:47.180 --> 01:43:49.160
So you recover your
original gradient.

01:43:52.790 --> 01:43:54.350
OK, that's the intensity.

01:43:54.350 --> 01:43:56.760
And you can also see
from this-- you can also

01:43:56.760 --> 01:44:00.600
get the condition for the
second harmonic generation.

01:44:00.600 --> 01:44:02.580
Basically, if you
kill this term, which

01:44:02.580 --> 01:44:05.250
means that this quantity
becomes pi over 2,

01:44:05.250 --> 01:44:06.230
then this disappears.

01:44:06.230 --> 01:44:08.730
So all you're left is the cosine
squared, which is of course

01:44:08.730 --> 01:44:10.090
the second harmonic.

01:44:10.090 --> 01:44:16.300
So this is really delineated
in the next slide.

01:44:16.300 --> 01:44:18.460
If the propagation distance--

01:44:18.460 --> 01:44:20.830
if this quantity, this
is also non-dimensional.

01:44:20.830 --> 01:44:23.440
It is distance squares
over distance squared.

01:44:23.440 --> 01:44:26.890
If you propagate far
enough so that this equals

01:44:26.890 --> 01:44:30.100
an even integer, then
you get the replica

01:44:30.100 --> 01:44:31.690
of the original gradient.

01:44:31.690 --> 01:44:33.970
This is basically--
this quantity

01:44:33.970 --> 01:44:37.000
becomes a phase delay of 2 pi.

01:44:37.000 --> 01:44:42.690
If you get it to become equal to
[? n, ?] you call this distance

01:44:42.690 --> 01:44:44.580
a Talbot play.

01:44:44.580 --> 01:44:49.320
If you're get it to propagate
so that it is an odd integer,

01:44:49.320 --> 01:44:53.940
then it is pi that
shifts this term by pi.

01:44:53.940 --> 01:44:55.550
Basically, you flip the sign.

01:44:55.550 --> 01:44:56.860
Now the gradient has shifted.

01:44:56.860 --> 01:45:00.680
If you really do work it out,
you still get the same sinusoid

01:45:00.680 --> 01:45:03.430
but shifted by half a period.

01:45:03.430 --> 01:45:07.560
And finally, if you completely
eliminate the linear term

01:45:07.560 --> 01:45:09.210
by choosing--

01:45:09.210 --> 01:45:14.790
this tends to be pi over 2 or
3 pi over 2 or 5 pi over 2,

01:45:14.790 --> 01:45:18.120
and so on and so forth,
then you can actually get--

01:45:18.120 --> 01:45:20.380
I forgot to put to
close my bracket here,

01:45:20.380 --> 01:45:24.060
but anyway, then you
get the period doubled.

01:45:24.060 --> 01:45:27.270
And you'll get the
second harmonic.

01:45:27.270 --> 01:45:30.070
OK, and this the schematic.

01:45:30.070 --> 01:45:32.380
These are basically now
repeating periodically

01:45:32.380 --> 01:45:37.860
every time you add this
propagation distance--

01:45:37.860 --> 01:45:41.250
I'm sorry, these
are flipped here.

01:45:41.250 --> 01:45:44.940
This should have been 2 lambda
z over lambda squared, 2 lambda

01:45:44.940 --> 01:45:46.210
z over lambda squared.

01:45:46.210 --> 01:45:49.410
So basically every time you
propagate by this quantity,

01:45:49.410 --> 01:45:51.540
you go from a Talbot
sub plane where

01:45:51.540 --> 01:45:54.580
you have a second
harmonic to a half period

01:45:54.580 --> 01:45:58.760
shift, to another second
harmonic to a replica.

01:45:58.760 --> 01:46:00.000
And then it repeats.

01:46:00.000 --> 01:46:02.790
So these are the Talbot plains.

01:46:02.790 --> 01:46:06.280
Now we're out of
time so I will say

01:46:06.280 --> 01:46:07.870
something that's
interesting for those

01:46:07.870 --> 01:46:12.150
of you who have time to stay.

01:46:12.150 --> 01:46:15.670
This-- as Professor
Sheppard mentioned

01:46:15.670 --> 01:46:18.860
has been noticed since
a very long time ago.

01:46:18.860 --> 01:46:21.950
But more recently, it became
actually kind of a hot topic

01:46:21.950 --> 01:46:24.730
over [INAUDIBLE]
because people noticed

01:46:24.730 --> 01:46:29.740
that it happens not only
in sinusoidal gradients,

01:46:29.740 --> 01:46:34.180
but it can also happen in
every periodic pattern.

01:46:34.180 --> 01:46:36.700
If, for example, you
have a square gradient,

01:46:36.700 --> 01:46:39.562
it would also have
its own Talbot planes.

01:46:39.562 --> 01:46:41.020
And then, not only
that, but people

01:46:41.020 --> 01:46:47.570
noticed that it can happen
in some strange patterns that

01:46:47.570 --> 01:46:50.560
are called was quasi-crystals.

01:46:50.560 --> 01:46:53.260
So I don't know how many of you
have taken solid state physics.

01:46:53.260 --> 01:46:56.020
But in solid state
physics they teach you

01:46:56.020 --> 01:47:02.132
that there are certain
patterns in nature that--

01:47:06.640 --> 01:47:09.258
there's often
symmetries in nature.

01:47:09.258 --> 01:47:10.800
For example, a very
simple symmetries

01:47:10.800 --> 01:47:12.370
is rectangular symmetry.

01:47:12.370 --> 01:47:17.620
If you take this as a unit
cell and then you repeat it,

01:47:17.620 --> 01:47:20.500
you can keep filling out the
space like this periodically.

01:47:20.500 --> 01:47:23.130
Another example is a hexagon.

01:47:23.130 --> 01:47:26.253
Let's see if I know
how to do the hexagon.

01:47:26.253 --> 01:47:27.420
I ended up doing an octagon.

01:47:27.420 --> 01:47:28.128
Sorry about that.

01:47:34.840 --> 01:47:37.220
That's a pentagon.

01:47:37.220 --> 01:47:38.410
I need one more, OK.

01:47:38.410 --> 01:47:39.460
I got my hexagon, OK.

01:47:39.460 --> 01:47:45.390
That's nice because
this does repeat.

01:47:45.390 --> 01:47:48.970
OK, never mind anyway.

01:47:53.440 --> 01:47:56.570
OK, that will repeat.

01:47:56.570 --> 01:47:57.070
Good.

01:48:00.500 --> 01:48:03.770
OK, so fortunately I
did a pentagon also.

01:48:08.042 --> 01:48:09.500
So the question is
what will happen

01:48:09.500 --> 01:48:13.350
if you start sticking
pentagons next to each other.

01:48:13.350 --> 01:48:16.760
Now this will be really
impossible for me to do,

01:48:16.760 --> 01:48:18.890
but you can imagine
if you tried to stick

01:48:18.890 --> 01:48:22.730
another pentagon, identical
pentagon next to here,

01:48:22.730 --> 01:48:27.860
then you will get something
like this, I guess.

01:48:27.860 --> 01:48:29.680
And then you can keep doing it.

01:48:29.680 --> 01:48:33.650
But you noticed when I did it,
then I got to stick a pentagon

01:48:33.650 --> 01:48:35.990
but it is slightly rotated.

01:48:35.990 --> 01:48:38.150
It is still is
difficult for me to draw

01:48:38.150 --> 01:48:41.570
but if you google
quasi-crystals.

01:48:46.522 --> 01:48:48.730
I don't know if it's the
first website that comes up.

01:48:48.730 --> 01:48:51.250
There's a website at Caltech,
in the physics department

01:48:51.250 --> 01:48:51.910
at Caltech.

01:48:51.910 --> 01:48:54.310
And you will see some
very nice pictures

01:48:54.310 --> 01:48:57.670
of what happens if you stick
pentagons next to each other.

01:48:57.670 --> 01:48:59.860
That's called a quasi-crystal.

01:48:59.860 --> 01:49:01.610
OK, now why are people
interested in this?

01:49:01.610 --> 01:49:04.450
Physicists are interested
because in solid state

01:49:04.450 --> 01:49:07.870
they teach you that if
you have atoms arranged

01:49:07.870 --> 01:49:13.180
in one of the patterns that
produce symmetries, then

01:49:13.180 --> 01:49:18.240
if you pass X-rays through
this symmetric lattice,

01:49:18.240 --> 01:49:20.250
you get a diffraction
pattern, very

01:49:20.250 --> 01:49:23.250
similar to a gradient
that we saw here,

01:49:23.250 --> 01:49:25.920
except that we're in 3D
because the symmetries are

01:49:25.920 --> 01:49:27.030
very simple in 2D.

01:49:27.030 --> 01:49:28.620
I think in 2D you only get two--

01:49:28.620 --> 01:49:31.188
you get the rectangular
and the hexagonal symmetry.

01:49:31.188 --> 01:49:32.730
In 3D, you get many
more symmetries--

01:49:32.730 --> 01:49:34.110
I forget, how many do you get?

01:49:34.110 --> 01:49:38.680
I think it is 7 groups
or 12 or anyway.

01:49:38.680 --> 01:49:40.430
I should refresh my
solid state physics.

01:49:40.430 --> 01:49:44.650
But anyway, each one of
these gives rise to--

01:49:44.650 --> 01:49:48.350
each symmetry gives rise to a
distinct diffraction pattern.

01:49:48.350 --> 01:49:49.870
And then crystallographers
basically

01:49:49.870 --> 01:49:51.610
bypass the next
stage to a crystal

01:49:51.610 --> 01:49:53.560
and observe the
diffraction pattern--

01:49:53.560 --> 01:49:56.170
they can guess what was
the original symmetry that

01:49:56.170 --> 01:49:58.220
produced it.

01:49:58.220 --> 01:50:01.670
We also know that non
symmetric patterns

01:50:01.670 --> 01:50:03.290
can produce diffraction.

01:50:03.290 --> 01:50:06.680
And that is what won Crick
and Watson the Nobel Prize

01:50:06.680 --> 01:50:09.210
because they figured out
that you have a helix, which

01:50:09.210 --> 01:50:11.620
not quite symmetric, it can
still produce a diffraction

01:50:11.620 --> 01:50:12.320
pattern.

01:50:12.320 --> 01:50:14.850
And Crick was a very clever
mathematician who solved it.

01:50:14.850 --> 01:50:17.240
And he won the
Nobel Prize for it.

01:50:17.240 --> 01:50:21.020
Anyway, recently people have
observed that quasi-crystals

01:50:21.020 --> 01:50:22.730
like this one-- if
you take pentagons

01:50:22.730 --> 01:50:24.500
and you stick them
next to each other,

01:50:24.500 --> 01:50:26.400
they also produce a
diffraction pattern,

01:50:26.400 --> 01:50:28.400
which looks actually
like a bunch

01:50:28.400 --> 01:50:33.907
of bright dots in a
pentagonal kind of symmetry.

01:50:33.907 --> 01:50:34.740
It looks very funny.

01:50:34.740 --> 01:50:38.760
If you go to this Caltech
website, you will see it.

01:50:38.760 --> 01:50:41.520
And then people also noticed
that this kind of thing

01:50:41.520 --> 01:50:44.010
also produces Talbot patterns.

01:50:44.010 --> 01:50:50.550
If you you diffract a field
from a pentagonal quasi-crystal,

01:50:50.550 --> 01:50:54.390
it will produce Talbot patterns
as you'll go behind it.

01:50:54.390 --> 01:50:56.340
And that caused
quite a bit of stir.

01:50:56.340 --> 01:51:00.600
Actually there's a lot of papers
analyzing this and looking

01:51:00.600 --> 01:51:01.860
into this interest.

01:51:01.860 --> 01:51:05.875
Anyway, so I don't know
if this has any use--

01:51:05.875 --> 01:51:07.250
it's kind of
interesting physics.

01:51:07.250 --> 01:51:11.020
But yeah, people spend
some time on that.

01:51:20.340 --> 01:51:20.840
Oh, yeah.

01:51:30.690 --> 01:51:33.480
Actually, Talbot effect
found a use recently

01:51:33.480 --> 01:51:38.350
in a very surprising
way in lithography.

01:51:38.350 --> 01:51:43.100
It is a very easy way to
reproduce a pattern lenslessly,

01:51:43.100 --> 01:51:46.590
as long as the
pattern is periodic.

01:51:46.590 --> 01:51:49.940
And so for planar
lithography is not

01:51:49.940 --> 01:51:52.100
that interesting,
but nowadays many

01:51:52.100 --> 01:51:55.780
people who want to make photonic
crystals which are periodic.

01:51:55.780 --> 01:51:58.710
So in the photonic crystals, you
want to start with the volume.

01:51:58.710 --> 01:52:00.380
So this is a
cross-section, and you

01:52:00.380 --> 01:52:05.280
want to write patterns
that look like this.

01:52:05.280 --> 01:52:08.630
So for example, what you
do is you take a polymer--

01:52:08.630 --> 01:52:09.710
OK, I take it back.

01:52:09.710 --> 01:52:14.000
You take a monomer and if you
could expose some [INAUDIBLE]

01:52:14.000 --> 01:52:19.018
these regions and
then you develop it,

01:52:19.018 --> 01:52:20.810
then you would end up
with a structure that

01:52:20.810 --> 01:52:24.530
has low index in the unexposed
regions and high index

01:52:24.530 --> 01:52:26.030
in exposed regions.

01:52:26.030 --> 01:52:28.090
That is a photonic crystal.

01:52:28.090 --> 01:52:29.820
So the question is
how could you do this.

01:52:29.820 --> 01:52:31.720
Well, one way is
with a Talbot effect

01:52:31.720 --> 01:52:34.520
because a Talbot effect will
actually focus the light very

01:52:34.520 --> 01:52:40.157
sharply in the Talbot planes and
then you'll get your exposure.

01:52:40.157 --> 01:52:42.240
But everywhere else, the
light is kind of diffuse.

01:52:42.240 --> 01:52:44.270
So it does not expose very much.

01:52:44.270 --> 01:52:47.660
So if you play with the
threshold of the photoresist,

01:52:47.660 --> 01:52:50.240
you can actually get the
pattern to work like this.

01:52:50.240 --> 01:52:52.360
So there's a colleague of
mine at MIT, Ned Thomas.

01:52:52.360 --> 01:52:54.830
I don't know if any of Ned's
students are in the class.

01:52:54.830 --> 01:52:57.200
But he came up with
a very clever system

01:52:57.200 --> 01:53:02.120
that he can expose and create
photonic crystals this way.

01:53:02.120 --> 01:53:04.460
And then interestingly,
a student of mine

01:53:04.460 --> 01:53:12.550
discovered that if you vary
the duty cycle of this thing,

01:53:12.550 --> 01:53:14.450
I may be disclosing--

01:53:14.450 --> 01:53:16.550
everybody here is MIT, right?

01:53:16.550 --> 01:53:19.100
And those of you who are
NUS are sort of bound

01:53:19.100 --> 01:53:21.150
by a vow of secrecy or whatever.

01:53:21.150 --> 01:53:22.990
But anyway, I may be
disclosing something

01:53:22.990 --> 01:53:24.710
that we have a
patent pending for.

01:53:24.710 --> 01:53:27.380
But anyway, so it
is also well known--

01:53:27.380 --> 01:53:34.360
people have analyzed
patterns with a duty cycle

01:53:34.360 --> 01:53:37.313
that these different
[INAUDIBLE] point have.

01:53:37.313 --> 01:53:39.730
So for example, if you have a
gradient that is like this--

01:53:43.130 --> 01:53:45.850
this also produces
a Talbot effect.

01:53:45.850 --> 01:53:49.470
So it will also produce
replicas of that pattern.

01:53:49.470 --> 01:53:52.315
So but my student discovered
that if you vary the duty

01:53:52.315 --> 01:53:54.440
cycle, that's really
interesting and we don't fully

01:53:54.440 --> 01:53:56.660
understand why but it is true.

01:53:56.660 --> 01:53:59.780
I mean, it is physically
correct-- we don't know how

01:53:59.780 --> 01:54:02.460
to explain it very intuitively.

01:54:02.460 --> 01:54:04.210
But mathematically,
you find that you have

01:54:04.210 --> 01:54:07.380
a pattern with a fixed period.

01:54:07.380 --> 01:54:16.810
But the variable duty cycle,
for example, like this,

01:54:16.810 --> 01:54:19.120
it also for this
is a Talbot effect.

01:54:19.120 --> 01:54:24.370
Not forever, but over a
finite region maybe about--

01:54:24.370 --> 01:54:27.030
I don't know, it depends but
maybe about 10 or so Talbot

01:54:27.030 --> 01:54:29.750
planes, it reproduces itself.

01:54:29.750 --> 01:54:32.772
So it is also possible to
make non-periodic patterns,

01:54:32.772 --> 01:54:35.230
which as [? Colin ?] knows,
we're very interested in making

01:54:35.230 --> 01:54:36.907
non-periodic kind of--

01:54:36.907 --> 01:54:38.740
they're not for [? tiny ?]
crystals anymore,

01:54:38.740 --> 01:54:42.340
but they're not periodic
strong index modulations.

01:54:42.340 --> 01:54:46.820
That is possibly
one way to do it.

01:54:46.820 --> 01:54:49.080
AUDIENCE: George,
it seems like it

01:54:49.080 --> 01:54:53.140
seems like that was still
a periodic pattern though.

01:54:53.140 --> 01:54:56.318
TA: No, because the
duty cycle varies.

01:54:56.318 --> 01:54:58.610
We call it periodic because
you must have the same duty

01:54:58.610 --> 01:55:00.500
cycle in every period.

01:55:00.500 --> 01:55:02.950
AUDIENCE: So even though
it repeats every period

01:55:02.950 --> 01:55:07.190
with a different duty
cycle, that's not periodic.

01:55:07.190 --> 01:55:10.345
TA: I don't know, would you
call this function periodic?

01:55:10.345 --> 01:55:12.470
AUDIENCE: I understand what
you mean about the duty

01:55:12.470 --> 01:55:15.155
cycle changing, but it's
got a definite period to it

01:55:15.155 --> 01:55:16.470
where features are--

01:55:16.470 --> 01:55:17.420
TA: Yeah.

01:55:17.420 --> 01:55:21.710
Yeah, but it's non-periodic.

01:55:21.710 --> 01:55:25.860
OK, what you're saying
is a possible explanation

01:55:25.860 --> 01:55:28.020
for why it has a Talbot effect.

01:55:28.020 --> 01:55:30.330
It has a Talbot
effect because it

01:55:30.330 --> 01:55:34.370
has this fundamental period
underlined the variable duty

01:55:34.370 --> 01:55:35.070
cycle.

01:55:35.070 --> 01:55:36.778
AUDIENCE: Right, I
look at the duty cycle

01:55:36.778 --> 01:55:39.720
as changing the orders
that are coming out

01:55:39.720 --> 01:55:41.160
for that particular region.

01:55:45.150 --> 01:55:47.700
TA: Well, in a slowly varying
approximation, perhaps.

01:55:47.700 --> 01:55:49.110
Yes.

01:55:49.110 --> 01:55:50.990
I mean, this thing--

01:55:50.990 --> 01:55:52.880
I've not looking at
the diffraction pattern

01:55:52.880 --> 01:55:53.880
of this thing in detail.

01:55:53.880 --> 01:55:57.810
But yes, it would produce
diffracted orders.

01:55:57.810 --> 01:56:01.860
But it is not clear how you
would compute their strength

01:56:01.860 --> 01:56:03.360
from a Fourier series.

01:56:03.360 --> 01:56:05.390
At least, I don't
know how to do it.

01:56:05.390 --> 01:56:09.800
There may be a way with somebody
adiabatic approximation.

01:56:09.800 --> 01:56:12.840
Because it is true
that in our simulation,

01:56:12.840 --> 01:56:15.890
the duty cycle was
very slowly varied.

01:56:15.890 --> 01:56:17.250
And I believe it is also true.

01:56:17.250 --> 01:56:18.542
In fact, I think Will--

01:56:18.542 --> 01:56:20.750
my student who did this--
he also did this simulation

01:56:20.750 --> 01:56:23.690
with a fast, varying duty
cycle, and he found out

01:56:23.690 --> 01:56:26.120
that the Talbot effect
actually does not happen

01:56:26.120 --> 01:56:28.280
if the duty cycle varies fast.

01:56:28.280 --> 01:56:29.210
So, yeah.

01:56:29.210 --> 01:56:34.130
There's certainly an adiabatic
approximation happening here.

01:56:34.130 --> 01:56:38.480
But I guess we haven't really
worked out all the details.

01:56:38.480 --> 01:56:40.910
But it is sort of
interesting still.

01:56:46.230 --> 01:56:51.180
Anyway, yeah, it's one
of those things that--

01:56:51.180 --> 01:56:53.710
the reason I'm bringing it up
is because the Talbot effect

01:56:53.710 --> 01:56:56.290
doesn't look like something
particularly useful.

01:56:56.290 --> 01:56:58.660
It looks more like a curiosity.

01:56:58.660 --> 01:57:00.830
But yeah, I guess
sometimes even curiosities

01:57:00.830 --> 01:57:03.220
can find applications, right?